National Transportation Safety Board
Aviation Accident Final Report
Location: Eufaula, AL
Accident Number: ERA12CA199
Date & Time: 03/01/2012, 1200 CST
Registration: N38FA
Aircraft: BELL OH-58A
Aircraft Damage: Substantial
Defining Event: Hard landing
Injuries: 2 None
Flight Conducted Under: Part 91: General Aviation - Instructional
 Analysis The pilot reported that he was conducting annual refresher training with a certified flight instructor.
During a practice autorotation to runway 18, the helicopter descended below a nearby tree line and then suddenly dropped.
He stated that the helicopter descended so rapidly that he was unable to arrest the descent rate and the helicopter landed hard.
The pilot reported that the wind was from 230 degrees at 10 knots with gusts to 19 knots at the time of the accident.
He reported that, as the helicopter descended below treetop level, "â€“we lost all lift and wind advantage."
The hard landing resulted in a fractured tail boom.
The pilots reported no mechanical malfunctions or failures that would have precluded normal operation.
Probable Cause and Findings The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be: The pilot's inadequate compensation for the gusting wind, which resulted in an excessive descent rate and hard landing.
